The Way to Nuclear Disarmament
NEW YORK – Mass destruction weapons and disarmament are one of the most difficult challenges we face today. One of my priorities as Secretary-General of the United Nations is to promote global well-being and find solutions to problems that disregard no borders.
A world without nuclear weapons is a common good of the highest importance.
My interest in this matter is partly based on personal experiences.
My home country, South Korea, has suffered under the devastations of conventional war and was exposed to the threat of nuclear weapons and other mass destruction weapons.
However, such threat scenarios are naturally not just limited to Asia.
Although the use of atomic weapons has long been considered taboo, disarmament remains merely an aspiration.
Is a taboo that only applies to the use of such weapons truly sufficient?
When it comes to nuclear weapons, it is individual states that make the most important decisions.
However, the UN plays a crucial role in this regard.
We offer a central forum in which states can agree on norms that serve their common interests.
We analyze and inform to achieve our agreed-upon goals and advocate for them.
Most states have decided to forgo atomic weapons and have consolidated their commitments under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
However, some states view such weapons as status symbols, and others see them as the ultimate deterrent against an attack with atomic weapons, which mainly explains the estimated 26,000 still existing weapons.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of nuclear deterrence is contagious, which makes non-proliferation more difficult and new risks emerge that atomic weapons will be used.
The world remains concerned about nuclear activities in North Korea and Iran, and there is broad support for efforts to address these concerns peacefully.
There are also concerns that we are facing a "nuclear renaissance" as nuclear energy is seen as a clean energy alternative in times of increasing efforts to combat climate change.
The main concern is that this will lead to the production and use of more nuclear material that must be protected from proliferation and terrorist threats.
The obstacles to disarmament are enormous.
However, the costs and risks of their alternatives never receive the attention they deserve.
Let's think about the enormous opportunity costs of high military budgets.
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (Stockholm Institute for International Peace Research), military expenditures rose to over $1.3 billion last year.
Ten years ago, the Brookings Institution published a study estimating the total costs of nuclear weapons alone in the United States at over $5.8 billion, including future maintenance costs.
That's a huge investment by any definition, which could have been used for many other productive goals.
Concerns about the costs of nuclear weapons and the dangers inherent in them have led to a global exchange of ideas on how nuclear disarmament could be given new life.
We experienced the UN disarmament commission under Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition and Norway's Seven Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan founded the International Commission on Nuclear Non-Proliferation and Disarmament.
Citizen groups and nuclear weapon-possessing states have also submitted proposals, such as the Hoover Plan, which was introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my five-point plan.
Firstly: I call on all members of the nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, especially the nuclear powers, to adhere to their commitments under the treaty and enter into negotiations on effective measures that lead to nuclear disarmament.
They could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually reinforcing instruments.
Or they could negotiate a nuclear weapons convention that would be backed by a strong control system, as has been proposed in the UN for a long time.
I have sent a draft for such a convention, which provides a good starting point, to all UN member states.
The nuclear powers should engage actively with this issue at the UN Disarmament Conference in Geneva, the only multilateral negotiating forum for disarmament in the world, together with other states.
The world would also welcome a resumption of the bilateral negotiations between the United States and Russia, with the aim of strongly and verifiably reducing their arsenals.
The governments should also invest more in control research and development.
Britain's proposal to hold a conference of nuclear powers on the topic of control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Secondly: The permanent members of the Security Council should start discussing security issues in the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could clearly inform the states that do not possess atomic weapons that they will not be victims of an atomic weapons deployment or the threat thereof.
The Council could also convene a summit on nuclear disarmament.
States that are not members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty should stop their nuclear weapons programs and take on their own disarmament commitments.
Thirdly: One-sided moratoriums on nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials may only be allowed to a certain extent.
We need new efforts to bring the nuclear test ban treaty into force, as well as stimuli to ensure that the disarmament conference takes up negotiations on a treaty on fissile materials immediately and without conditions.
I support the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly advocate for efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
Furthermore, I urgently call on all members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty to conclude their security agreements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily implement the stricter security clauses of the additional protocol.
Fourthly: Nuclear powers often circulate descriptions of the steps they take to achieve these goals.
However, these reports rarely reach the public.
I would like to ask the nuclear powers to send such materials to the UN Secretariat and contribute to their further dissemination.
The fact that there is no authoritative estimate of the total number of nuclear weapons confirms the need for greater transparency.
And finally, various additional measures are necessary.
To this end include the elimination of other types of mass destruction weapons, new efforts against terrorism with mass destruction weapons, a limitation on the production and trade of conventional weapons and new weapons bans, including for missiles and space weapons.
If there are real, confirmed progress in disarmament, the ability to eliminate the nuclear threat will grow exponentially.
By gradually eliminating the deadliest weapons in the world and their components, we make it harder to carry out terrorist attacks with mass destruction weapons.
These proposals offer a new start, not only for disarmament, but also for strengthening our system of international peace and international security.
